# Intervertebral Disc

> The **intervertebral disc** is a fibrocartilaginous structure between adjacent vertebral bodies in the [[Vertebral Column]], acting as a shock absorber and allowing spinal flexibility. It consists of an outer **annulus fibrosus** and an inner **nucleus pulposus**.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Vertebral Column]] — located between each vertebral body (C2–3 to L5–S1)
- [[Spinal Cord]] — disc herniations compress adjacent nerve roots or the spinal cord
- [[Cervical Vertebrae]] — cervical discs; most mobile region
- [[Lumbar Vertebrae]] — lumbar discs; highest load; most commonly herniated (L4–L5, L5–S1)

## 🗂️ Anatomy
| Component | Structure | Function |
|-----------|-----------|----------|
| Annulus fibrosus | Concentric collagen rings | Contain nucleus; resist torsion |
| Nucleus pulposus | Gelatinous core (notochord remnant) | Distribute compressive forces |
| End plates | Cartilaginous; superior + inferior | Nutrient diffusion (avascular disc) |

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Disc herniation** — Nucleus pulposus extrudes through annular tear → nerve root compression
  - L4–L5: L5 root → dorsiflexion weakness, lateral leg/dorsal foot numbness
  - L5–S1: S1 root → plantarflexion weakness, lateral foot numbness, reduced ankle reflex
- **Discogenic back pain** — Annular tears causing axial low back pain without radiculopathy
- **Disc degeneration** — Loss of water content → disc height loss → foraminal narrowing → stenosis
- **Cauda equina syndrome** — Massive central herniation at L1–L2 or below → surgical emergency

